# Git release tagging on main

After every `git commit` + `git push` to the `main` branch, always tag the release and push the tag.

## Steps (run sequentially after the push)

```bash
# 1. Get the latest existing tag (defaults to v0.0.0 if none)
LATEST=$(git tag --sort=-v:refname | grep -E '^v[0-9]+\.[0-9]+\.[0-9]+$' | head -1)
LATEST=${LATEST:-v0.0.0}

# 2. Bump the patch version  (v1.2.3 → v1.2.4)
IFS='.' read -r major minor patch <<< "${LATEST#v}"
NEW_TAG="v${major}.${minor}.$((patch + 1))"

# 3. Create annotated tag pointing at HEAD
git tag -a "$NEW_TAG" -m "Release $NEW_TAG"

# 4. Push the tag to origin
git push origin "$NEW_TAG"
```

## Version bump rules

| Change type | Bump | Example |
|---|---|---|
| Bug fix / small tweak | patch | v1.2.3 → v1.2.4 |
| New feature / new section | minor | v1.2.3 → v1.3.0 |
| Breaking redesign / major new product area | major | v1.2.3 → v2.0.0 |

Default to **patch** unless the commit clearly introduces a new feature (minor) or breaking change (major).

## Notes

- Always use annotated tags (`-a`) so the tag has a message visible on GitHub.
- Never skip tagging even for small commits — every push to main is a release.
- If the push fails (e.g. not yet pushed to remote), skip the tag step and remind the user to tag manually after the push succeeds.
